Captured a Moment in Nature: Delias eucharis Butterfly ü¶ã

I had the incredible opportunity to photograph the stunning Delias eucharis butterfly, also known as the white-banded jay, in its natural habitat. üèûÔ∏è

This beautiful creature, with its striking white and black wings, was fluttering around the tropical forests of Southeast Asia. It‚Äôs amazing how nature creates such intricate patterns and vibrant colors. üåø

The Delias eucharis thrives in high-altitude forests, where it feeds on the nectar of wildflowers. Their quick, erratic flight and delicate movements make them a true marvel to watch and capture through the lens. üì∏

Grateful for moments like these that remind us of the beauty in the world around us. üåçüíö

Dear All,
We are pleased to announce that the 12th annual ‚ÄòButterfly Fair-2023‚Äô is ready to roll at this moment. A Photography Competition will be held at the Fair. The theme of the competition is "Butterflies of Bangladesh". The goal of this competition is to raise public awareness about the need to conserve this magnificent pollinator and its habitat. This competition and exhibition will allow you to demonstrate your enthusiasm and skill for butterfly photography in Bangladesh.
Photo Submission to: monwarbutterfly@gmail.com
Submission deadline: 17th Nov 2023, 11.00 PM
Primary selection announcement: 19th Nov, 2023
Final selection announcement: 24th Nov, 2023
Terms and conditions of entry:
1. Butterfly with its natural habitat, foraging, mating, emerged from pupa, caterpillar, and puddling images will be greatly appreciated. Photos must be taken in Bangladesh.
2. Captive butterfly images are not eligible.
3. Butterfly with any manipulation is not eligible.
4. Image can be rejected if that makes any sense to breach country‚Äôs wildlife acts.
5. A participant can submit a maximum of two photographs.
6. Digital manipulation, stitching different frames, copyright signs, watermarks, logos, HDR, or any sort of alteration will result in disqualification from the competition without prior notice.
7. Photos must be in JPEG or JPG format and should be at least 3000 pixels on the longer side. The minimum resolution of the image is 300 dpi.
8. Rename each photo in the following format: participant‚Äôs name, Mobile no. For example:
Khayrul Hasan_01726XXXXXX
9. The best three photographs will be awarded. Any decision taken by the organizers and the judges in selecting the photographs will be the final decision.
NO REGISTRATION FEE IS REQUIRED
Thanks.

An important conclusion drawn out of this study by Irungbam et al. (2023):
The Asian population of one grass yellow butterflies widely assigned to species Eurema brigitta is actually Eurema drona, since genetic as well as morphological analyses suggest that true Eurema brigitta is restricted to Africa and Madagascar. 

Read more from here: Irungbam, M., Irungbam, J.S., Rindos, M., Maresova, J.P. & Fric, Z.F. (2023) Phylogeography of the small grass yellow Eurema brigitta (Stoll, 1780) (Lepidoptera: Pieridae) unveils the existence of distinct taxa within the Palaeotropics. Austral Entomology,1‚Äì7. UnH purple brown with a silky gloss, (much visible in a flashed photo)

A short tail at vein 2

Theme: ‚ÄúButterflies of Bangladesh‚Äù
Dear All,
We are pleased to announce that 12th annual ‚ÄòButterfly Fair-2022‚Äô is ready to roll at this moment. A Photography Competition will be held at the Fair. The theme of the competition is "Butterflies of Bangladesh". The goal of this competition is to raise public awareness about the need to conserve this magnificent pollinator and its habitat. This competition and exhibition will allow you to demonstrate your enthusiasm and skill for butterfly photography in Bangladesh.
Photo Submission to: monwarbutterfly@gmail.com
Submission deadline: 18th Nov 2022, 12.00 PM
Primary selection announcement: 21th Nov, 2022
Final selection announcement: 2nd Dec, 2022
Terms and conditions of entry:
1. Butterfly with its natural habitat, foraging, mating, emerged from pupa, caterpillar and puddling images will be greatly appreciated. Photos must be taken in Bangladesh.
2. Captive butterfly images are not eligible.
3. Butterfly with any manipulation is not eligible.
4. Image can be rejected if that makes any sense to breach country‚Äôs wildlife acts.
5. A participant can submit a maximum of two photographs.
6. Digital manipulation, stitching different frames, copyright signs, watermarks, logos, HDR, or any sort of alteration will result in disqualification from the competition without prior notice.
7. Photos must be in JPEG or JPG format and should be at least 3000 pixels on the longer side. The minimum resolution of the image is 300 dpi.
8. Rename each photo in the following format: participant‚Äôs name, Mobile no. For example:
Khayrul Hasan_01726XXXXXX
9. Best three photographs will be awarded. Any decision taken by the organizers and the judges in selecting the photographs will be the final decision.
10. A certificate and laminated photo will be provided to all primary selected participants.
NO REGISTRATION FEE IS REQUIRED

Second talk in the series of talks organised by Bangalore Butterfly Club on butterfly awareness and conservation is scheduled on 7th May, Saturday at 18.00 IST.

Please join using the link given below

_
Insect populations including butterflies are declining worldwide, and they are becoming an urgent conservation priority in many regions. Understanding which butterfly species migrate is critical to planning for their conservation because management actions for migrants need to be coordinated across time and space. Yet, while migration appears to be widespread among butterflies, its prevalence, as well as its taxonomic and geographic distribution is poorly understood. In this seminar, Shawan Chowdhury  will talk about trends and progress in studying butterfly migration, global gaps in butterfly migration studies, seasonal dynamics of butterfly migration, rapid range expansion, and conserving butterflies in protected areas.

The link to join the talk https://msteams.link/VSSW

Genus Telicota of Bangladesh. 
Generally we compare Telicota colon vs Telicota bambusae by : 

1. UpF dark border at termen more or less penetrated by yellow-edged veins in Telicota colon (Pale Palm-dart)

Versus, UpF termen not penetrated by yellow-edged veins in Telicota bambusae. ( Dark Palm-dart )

2. In Telicota colon, stigma ( male sex brand ) is broad and placed nearer to the inner edge of central band  vs stigma placed nearer to the outer edge of central band in Telicota bambusae.

When the UpF termen is heavily crossed or penetrated by Yellow-edged veins we can strongly predict a Telicota colon . 

But problem arises when the yellow-edged veins are less penetrated through the termen. 

( According to Evans , in DSF Telicota ancilla bambusae= Telicota bambusae bambusae 

UpF dark borders along termen may be traversed by yellow veins as in colon ) 

Now without Genitalia examination or proper study we are also ruling out Telicota linna which is very similar and a close contender to Telicota bambusae and of course should be found in our vicinity ( North east or elsewhere) according to Evans‚Äô distribution. 

So my opinion is that except the Telicota colon ( male , where UpF black border at termen strongly crossed by yellow-edged veins ) , Telicota bambusae should be considered as Telicota sp. unless proven by genitalia examination as Telicota linna should be found in our country .

‡¶ó‡¶§ ‡¶¨‡¶õ‡¶∞ ‡¶•‡ßá‡¶ï‡ßá Arhopala (Oakblue) Genus ‡¶è‡¶∞ ‡¶è‡¶á ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ú‡¶æ‡¶™‡¶§‡¶ø‡¶ü‡¶ø ‡¶®‡¶ú‡¶∞‡ßá ‡¶™‡¶°‡¶º‡¶õ‡ßá ‡•§ ‡¶¶‡ßá‡¶ñ‡¶§‡ßá ‡¶Ö‡¶®‡ßá‡¶ï‡¶ü‡¶æ‡¶á Green Oakblue ( Arhopala eumolphus ) ‡¶è‡¶∞ ‡¶Æ‡¶§‡ßã , ‡¶ï‡¶ø‡¶®‡ßç‡¶§‡ßÅ Underwings View ‡¶Ö‡¶®‡ßá‡¶ï ‡¶∏‡¶æ‡¶¶‡¶æ‡¶ü‡ßá , ‡¶Ø‡¶æ ‡¶Æ‡¶®‡ßá ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡ßá ‡¶¶‡ßá‡¶Ø‡¶º Doherty‚Äôs Green Oakblue  (Arhopala hellenore hellenore) ‡¶è‡¶∞ ‡¶ï‡¶•‡¶æ , ‡¶Ø‡ßá‡¶ü‡¶ø ‡¶¨‡¶æ‡¶Ç‡¶≤‡¶æ‡¶¶‡ßá‡¶∂‡ßá‡¶∞ ‡¶ö‡¶ü‡ßç‡¶ü‡¶ó‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶æ‡¶Æ‡ßá ‡¶™‡¶æ‡¶ì‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ ‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶Ø‡¶º ‡¶¨‡¶≤‡ßá ‡¶â‡¶≤‡ßç‡¶≤‡ßá‡¶ñ ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡ßá‡¶õ‡ßá‡¶® ‡¶¨‡¶ø‡¶ñ‡ßç‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶§ Entomologist W.H Evans (1957) 

According to Evans, 
Arhopala hellenore hellenore has more or less variegated underwings . Coastal half of hindwing and apical half of forewing is more or less whitened. Termen of forewing straight. 
These all features goes with this specimen found. 

Now it is also mentioned that the border at upper forewing apex is not greater than half millimetre. This specimen has narrowed border at apex compared to Green oakblue . The degree of narrowness is comparable to the specimens of Arhopala hellenore hellenore found in Specimens of Yutkaa. 

http://yutaka.it-n.jp/lyc4f/82470001.html

NB: The upper forewing colour can look purplish green due to the surrounding lights. By naked eye this is really green . The photographs at the end of the page of yutaka also goes with purplish green colour 

http://yutaka.it-n.jp/lyc4f/82470001.html
